paragraph.text:
in 1989, the United States Fish and Wildlife Service (referred to in this section as the Service) listed the American burying beetle as an endangered species under the 
            Endangered Species Act (16
			 U.S.C. 1531 et seq.);

subparagraph.text:
considered
			 possible factors in the population decline of the American burying beetle,
			 but ultimately concluded that the cause of the species’ decline is unknown;

paragraph.text:
as of the date of the decision, there were only 2 known populations of the American burying beetle,
			 1 located in Eastern Oklahoma and 1 located on an island off the coast of
			 Rhode Island;

at that time, the	Rhode Island population was estimated to be around 520 American burying
			 beetles and the Oklahoma
			 population to be fewer than 12 American burying beetles;

in 1991, the Service published a recovery plan for the American
			 burying beetle, with the objective of protecting and maintaining the
			 extant population in Rhode Island and the populations in Oklahoma;

subparagraph.text:
the historic range of the American burying beetle,
			 described by the Service as being ubiquitous at some point, is reliant on data, observations, and studies that are more than 70 years old and
			 are not easy to locate;
